.TH sccs-istext 1 "2020/09/10" "J\*org Schilling" "Schily\'s USER COMMANDS"
.SH NAME
sccs-istext \- check whether files are text files or need to be encoded
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B
sccs istext
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ file1 " .. " filen ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B sccs istext
subcommand checks whether the files are pure text files or whether they need
to be encoded.
.LP
This subcommand is a
.B \s-1SCHILY\s+1
extension that does not exist in historic
.B sccs
implementations.
. \" .SH RETURNS
. \" .SH ERRORS
.SH OPTIONS
.LP
.TP
.B \-D
Print the current default history file format. This is the history file format
assumed in case that neither
.B \-V4
nor
.B \-V6
have been specified.
No file argument is permitted when this option has been specified.
.TP
.B \-s
Be silent. If all files are pure text, the exit code is 0.
.TP
.B \-V4
Check with
.B SCCS\ v4
rules.
A file is not pure text if it contains one or more null characters,
if a line starts with \e001 (^A) or if the file does not end with
a newline character.
.TP
.B \-V6
Check with
.B SCCS\ v6
rules.
A file is not pure text if it contains one or more null characters.

.SH EXAMPLES
.LP
To check wheter the file
.B xec.c
in the current directory is a pure text file, call:
.IP
.B "sccs istext xec.c"
